<section xml:id="sec-section-Pythagorean-relationship" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Pythagorean relationship</title>
 <p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        A triangle that contains a right angle 
        (an angle that measures <m>90^\circ</m>, symbolized by a small square "â–¡") is
        called a right triangle.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        The longest side of the right triangle (the side opposite the <m>90^\circ</m> angle)
        is called the hypotenuse and the other two (shorter) sides 
        are called the legs of the triangle.

      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        The legs of a right triangle are commonly labelled
        <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> while the hypotenuse 
        is labeled <m>c</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
 </p>
  <image width="50%">
  <latex-image>
    \begin{tikzpicture}
      \draw [thick,fill=cyan](0,0)  --(0,5) --(5,0) --(0,0);
      \draw (0,0) --(0,0.5) --(0.5,0.5) --(0.5,0) --(0,0);
      \node at (-1,2.5){height (b) };
      \node at (3.9,2.5){Hypotenuse (c)};
      \node at (2.5,-0.5){base (a)};
      \node at (-1,0.3){Right angle};
      
    \end{tikzpicture}
  </latex-image>
         
  </image>


  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The Pythagorean relationship is a special rule about right-angled triangles. 
          It helps us find the length of one side if we know the other two sides.
        </p>
        <p>
          We use the Pythagorean relationship in many real-life situations, such as: 
          <me>{\color{green} \text{Carpentry}}\text{: To design classrooms, furniture and divide land into plots.}</me>
          <me>{\color{green}\text{ Building and Room Design}}\text{: For example, when building classrooms or arranging furniture.}</me>
          <me>{\color{green} \text{Sports}}\text{: In games like basketball, soccer, or football, it helps measure distances, like how far a player runs or the shortest path to the goal.}</me>
        </p>
        
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          A long time ago, about 2000 years back, 
          people discovered something amazing about right-angled triangles. They found that:
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>{\color{green} \text{If you make squares on each side of a right-angled triangle, 
          the area of the two smaller squares adds up to the area of the largest square.}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          In other words, the two small squares together are exactly the same size as the big square.
        </p>
        <image source="/Rightangle-triangle.png" width="50%">
          <shortdescription>The ubove description for about 2000 years</shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          This special rule is called the Pythagorean Theorem, and we write it as: <me>a^2+b^2=c^2</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Where,
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>a </m> and <m>b </m> are the shorter sides of the triangle.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>c </m> is the longest side (called the hypotenuse).
        </p>
      </li>
    
    </ul>
  </p>


  
  <activity> 
    
    <statement>
      <p>
         Work in Groups.
      </p>
      <p>
        Read the story below.
      </p>
      <sidebyside>
        <p>
          Cherotich and Onyango are Grade 7 learners. During the 
          August holiday, they visited their grandmother, who lives 
          nearby a village. Their grandmother is a grocer. 
          Cherotich and Onyango help there grandmother to fetch fruits from 
          a tree for selling. Cherotich used a <m>10\,m</m> ladder to climb the fruit 
          tree. The ladder had its foot <m>6\,m</m> from the bottom of the tree 
          and leaned on the tree at the height of <m>8\,m</m>.
        </p>
    
        <image source="/Tree-harriet.png" width="40%">
          <shortdescription>The tree</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
        <p>
          <m>{\color{blue}\textit{Learning point}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Draw the figure that has been formed between the tree, 
                ladder and the ground?
  
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                How many sides does it have?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Which is the longest side of the figure?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Identify the two shorter sides of the figure.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Name the side of the figure. You may use digital devices 
                to research on the internet.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Share your findings with other leaners in class.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Here is the correct Learning point.
      </p>
      <sidebyside>
        <image>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw [thick,fill=green](0,0) --(5,5) --(5,0) --(0,0);
            \draw (4.5,0) --(4.5,0.5) --(5,0.5) --(5,0) --(4.5,0);
            \node at (2.5,3){$10 \, m$};
            \node at (5.5,2.5){$8 \, m$};
            \node at (2.5,-0.5){$6 \, m$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
         
        </image>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                The figure formed between the tree, ladder 
                and the ground is a right-angled tringle.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                A right-angle triangle has three sides: 
                the <em>base</em>, the <em>perpendicular height</em> 
                and the <em>hypotenuse</em>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The side that is <m>8 m</m> long is the <em>perpendicular height</em>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The side that is <m>6 m</m> long is the <em>base</em>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The side that is <m>10 m</m> long is the <em>hypotenuse</em>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The longest side in a right-angled triangle is 
                the <em>hypotenuse</em>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The two shorter sides of this figure are the 
                <em>base</em> and the <em>perpendicular height</em>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </sidebyside>
    </solution>
  </activity>
  <p>
    <m>{\color{blue}\text{The pythagorean relationship.}}</m>
  </p>
  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          It state that, the sum of the squares of the 
          two shorter sides is equal to the squre of the 
          longer side (hypotenuse).
        </p>
       </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <sidebyside>
    <image  width="50%">
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}
        % Draw the triangle
        \fill[yellow!50] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (0,3) -- cycle;
        
        % Draw the triangle outline
        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (0,3) -- cycle;
        
        % Label vertices
        \node[below left] at (0,0) {A};
        \node[below right] at (4,0) {B};
        \node[above left] at (0,3) {C};
        
        % Label sides
        \node[below] at (2,0) { \(a\)};
        \node[left] at (0,1.5) { \(b\)};
        \node[above right] at (2,1.5) { \(c\)};
        \node[above right] at (2,2.5)   {\(a^2+b^2=c^2\)};
        
        % Right angle symbol
        \draw (0,0) rectangle ++(0.3,0.3);

      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
      
    </image>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            From the figure alongside, side <m>a</m> is the <m>{\color{blue}\text{base}}</m>,
            side b is the <m>{\color{blue}\text{height}}</m> and side c is the 
            <m>{\color{blue}\text{hypotenuse}}</m>.Therefore the relationship is, <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The relationship can be changed depending on the question 
            asked  on the length to calculate as shown below.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <me>
              c^2=a^2+b^2
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>b^2= \amp c^2-a^2</mrow>
              <mrow>a^2= \amp c^2-b^2</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </li>
     
      </ul>
    </p>

  </sidebyside>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the length of the side marked y in 
        the right-angled triangle below.
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
          % Draw the triangle
          \fill[white!50] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (0,3) -- cycle;
          
          % Draw the triangle outline
          \draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (0,3) -- cycle;
          

          
          % Label sides
          \node[below] at (2,0) { \(6\,cm\)};
          \node[left] at (0,1.5) { \(8\,cm\)};
          \node[above right] at (2,1.5) { \(y\)};
          
          
          % Right angle symbol
          \draw (0,0) rectangle ++(0.3,0.3);  


        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
        
      </image>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        To find the length of any side of the right-angled triangle, we use the 
        pythagorean relationship which state that: <m>c^2=a^2+b^2 </m>.
      </p>
    </hint>
    
    <solution>

      <p>
        In the above example,
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> a=\amp 6\,cm </mrow>
          <mrow> b=\amp 8\,cm </mrow>
          <mrow> c=\amp y </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Therefore,
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> y^2=\amp (8 cm)^2+ (6 cm)^2 </mrow>
          <mrow> y^2=\amp(8 cm \times 8 cm)+ (6cm \times 6 cm) </mrow>
          <mrow> y^2=\amp 64 cm^2 +36 cm^2 </mrow>
          <mrow> y^2=\amp 100 cm^2 </mrow>
          <mrow> y=\amp \sqrt{100 cm^2} </mrow>
          <mrow> y=\amp 10 cm </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Therefore,
      </p>
      <p>
        side <m>y</m> is <m>10\,cm</m>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the length of <m> w </m> in the figure below.
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
          \draw [thick,fill=blue] (0,4) --(4,4) --(4,0) --(0,4);
          \node at (2,1){$40 \,cm$};
          \node at (2,4.5){$w \,cm$};
          \node at (4.5,2){$24 \,cm$};
          \draw (3.5,3.5) --(3.5,4) --(4,4) --(4,3.5) --(3.5,3.5);
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
        
      </image>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> w^2=\amp (40^2-24^2)\,cm </mrow>
          <mrow> w^2=\amp 1\,600\,cm^2 - 576\,cm^2</mrow>
          <mrow> w^2=\amp 1\,024\,cm^2</mrow>
          <mrow> w=\amp \sqrt{1\,024\,cm^2} </mrow>
          <mrow> w=\amp 32\,cm </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Therefore the length of <m>w</m> is <m>32\,cm</m>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In the triangle find the size of line <m> PQ </m>
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
          \draw [thick,fill=white](0,0) coordinate (A)-- (0,5) coordinate (B)-- (5,0) coordinate (C)-- (0,0)coordinate (A);
          \node at (0,-0.5){R};
          \node at (0,5.5){P};
          \node at (5,-0.5){Q};
          \node at (-1,2.5){18cm};
          \node at (3,2.5){};
          \node at (2.5,-0.5){24 cm};
          \draw(0,0) coordinate (A)-- (0,0.5) coordinate (B)-- (0.5,0.5) coordinate (C)-- (0.5,0) coordinate(D)-- (0,0) coordinate (A);
       \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
      </image>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> PQ^2=\amp (QR^2+PR^2)\,cm </mrow>
          <mrow> PQ^2=\amp (24^2 + 18^2)\,cm^2</mrow>
          <mrow> PQ^2=\amp 576cm^2 + 324\,cm^2</mrow>
          <mrow> PQ^2=\amp \sqrt{900\,cm^2} </mrow>
          <mrow> PQ=\amp 30\,cm </mrow>
        </md>
  
      </p>
      <p>
        Therefore the length of <m>PQ</m> is <m>30\,cm</m>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
  <p>
    <m>{\color{green} \text{Application for pythagorean relationship}}</m>
  </p>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The base of a ladder is <m>5\,m</m> from the base of a vertical 
        wall. A painter places the ladder such that it touches the top of the 
        wall at a point <m>12\,m</m> above the ground.calculate the length 
        of the ladder (c).
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              It is appropriate for the learner to draw the figure as discribed in the 
              question above.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use the pythagorean relationship that is; <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The figure below shows the sketch of the ladder placced on the wall.
      </p>
      <image width="50%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
          \draw [very thick,fill=blue] (6,0) --(6,8);
          \draw [thick,fill=white] (0,0) --(6,6) --(6,0)--(0,0);
          \draw [very thick,fill=blue] (-1,0)--(6,7);
          \draw[very thick](-0.5,0.5) --(0,0);
          \draw[very thick](-0.4,0.6)--(0.1,0.1);
          \draw[very thick](0.3,1.3) --(0.8,0.8);
          \draw[very thick](0.4,1.4) --(0.9,0.9);
          \draw[very thick](1,2) --(1.5,1.5);
          \draw[very thick](1.1,2.1) --(1.6,1.6);
          \draw[very thick](2,3) --(2.5,2.5);
          \draw[very thick](2.1,3.1) --(2.6,2.6);
          \draw[very thick](3,4) --(3.5,3.5);
          \draw[very thick](3.1,4.1) --(3.6,3.6);
          \draw[very thick](4,5) --(4.5,4.5);
          \draw[very thick](4.1,5.1) --(4.6,4.6);
          \draw[very thick](5,6) --(5.5,5.5);
          \draw[very thick](5.1,6.1) --(5.6,5.6);
          \node at (3,-0.5){$5\,m$};
          \node at (6.5,3){$12\,m$};
          \node at (3,2){$c$};

        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
      
      </image>

      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> c^2=\amp(5^2+12^2)\,m^2 </mrow>
          <mrow> c^2= \amp(25+144)\,m^2 </mrow>
          <mrow> c^2=\amp 169 \,m^2 </mrow>
          <mrow> c=\amp \sqrt{169 \,m^2}</mrow>
          <mrow> c=\amp 13 \,m</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Therefore,the length of the ladder (c) is <m>{\color{blue} 13\,m}</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>



 
 
 

